<br><h3>Pythagorean Theorem</h3>
<p>The Pythagorean Theorem, also known as Pythagoras' theorem, is a fundame=
ntal relation between the three sides of a right triangle. Given a right tr=
iangle, which is a triangle in which one of the angles is 90=C2=B0, the Pyt=
hagorean theorem states that the area of the square formed by the longest s=
ide of the right triangle (the hypotenuse) is equal to the sum of the area =
of the squares formed by the other two sides of the right triangle:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfro=
nt.net/img/pythagorean-theorem-2.png" width=3D"294" height=3D"265" alt=3D"p=
ythagorean theorem"></p>
<p>In other words, given that the longest side c =3D the hypotenuse, and a =
and b =3D the other sides of the triangle:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup> =3D c<sup>2</=
sup></p>
<p>This is known as the Pythagorean equation, named after the ancient Greek=
 thinker Pythagoras. This relationship is useful because if two sides of a =
right triangle are known, the Pythagorean theorem can be used to determine =
the length of the third side. Referencing the above diagram, if</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">a =3D 3 and b =3D 4</p>
<p>the length of c can be determined as:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">c =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decorati=
on:overline;">a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></span> =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=
=3D"text-decoration:overline;">3<sup>2</sup>+4<sup>2</sup></span> =3D =E2=
=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;">25</span> =3D 5</p>
<p>It follows that the length of a and b can also be determined if the leng=
ths of the other two sides are known using the following relationships:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">a =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decorati=
on:overline;">c<sup>2</sup> - b<sup>2</sup></span></p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">b =3D =E2=88=9A<span style=3D"text-decorati=
on:overline;">c<sup>2</sup> - a<sup>2</sup></span></p>
<p>The law of cosines is a generalization of the Pythagorean theorem that c=
an be used to determine the length of any side of a triangle if the lengths=
 and angles of the other two sides of the triangle are known. If the angle =
between the other sides is a right angle, the law of cosines reduces to the=
 Pythagorean equation.</p>
<p>There are a multitude of proofs for the Pythagorean theorem, possibly ev=
en the greatest number of any mathematical theorem.</p>

<p><b>Algebraic proof:</b></p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://d26tpo4cm8sb6k.cloudfro=
nt.net/img/pythagorean-theorem-3.png" width=3D"319" height=3D"180" alt=3D"p=
ythagorean theorem algebraic proof"></p>
<p>In the figure above, there are two orientations of copies of right trian=
gles used to form a smaller and larger square, labeled i and ii, that depic=
t two algebraic proofs of the Pythagorean theorem.</p>
<p>In the first one, i, the four copies of the same triangle are arranged a=
round a square with sides c. This results in the formation of a larger squa=
re with sides of length b + a, and area of (b + a)<sup>2</sup>. The sum of =
the area of these four triangles and the smaller square must equal the area=
 of the larger square such that:</p>
<table align=3D"center"><tbody><tr><td>(b + a)<sup>2</sup> =3D c<sup>2</sup=
> + 4</td><td><table cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0"><tbody><tr><td ali=
gn=3D"center">ab</td></tr><tr><td height=3D"1" bgcolor=3D"#000000"></td></t=
r><tr><td align=3D"center">2</td></tr></tbody></table></td><td> =3D c<sup>2=
</sup> + 2ab</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>which yields:</p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td>c<sup>2</sup> =3D</td><td>(b + a)<sup>2</sup> - 2ab</td></t=
r>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>b<sup>2</sup> + 2ab + a<sup>2</sup> - =
2ab</td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></td></tr=
>
</tbody></table>
<p>which is the Pythagorean equation.</p>
<p>In the second orientation shown in the figure, ii, the four copies of th=
e same triangle are arranged such that they form an enclosed square with si=
des of length b - a, and area (b - a)<sup>2</sup>. The four triangles with =
area </p><table cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" class=3D"inlinetable"><=
tbody><tr><td>ab</td></tr><tr><td height=3D"1" bgcolor=3D"#000000"></td></t=
r><tr><td align=3D"center">2</td></tr></tbody></table> also form a larger s=
quare with sides of length c. The area of the larger square must then equal=
 the sum of the areas of the four triangles and the smaller square such tha=
t:<p></p>
<table align=3D"center">
	<tbody><tr><td><table align=3D"center"><tbody><tr><td>(b - a)<sup>2</sup> =
+ 4</td><td><table cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0"><tbody><tr><td align=
=3D"center">ab</td></tr><tr><td height=3D"1" bgcolor=3D"#000000"></td></tr>=
<tr><td align=3D"center">2</td></tr></tbody></table></td><td> =3D</td></tr>=
</tbody></table></td><td>(b - a)<sup>2</sup> + 2ab</td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>b<sup>2</sup> - 2ab + a<sup>2</sup> + =
2ab</td></tr>
	<tr><td align=3D"right">=3D</td><td>a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</sup></td></tr=
>
</tbody></table>
<p>Since the larger square has sides c and area c<sup>2</sup>, the above ca=
n be rewritten as:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align:center;">c<sup>2</sup> =3D a<sup>2</sup> + b<sup>2</=
sup></p>
<p>which is again, the Pythagorean equation.</p>
<p>There are numerous other proofs ranging from algebraic and geometric pro=
ofs to proofs using differentials, but the above are two of the simplest ve=
rsions.</p>

